SIMPLE: threaten
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Threaten
<hw>Threat"en</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Threatened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Threatening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧retenen</ets>. See <er>Threat</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter threats against; to menace; to inspire with
apprehension; to alarm, or attempt to alarm, as with the promise of
something evil or disagreeable; to warn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let us straitly <qex>threaten</qex> them, that they speak
henceforth to no man in this name.</q> <rj><qau>Acts iv.
17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To exhibit the appearance of (something evil or
unpleasant) as approaching; to indicate as impending; to announce the
conditional infliction of; <as>as, to <ex>threaten</ex> war; to
<ex>threaten</ex> death</as>.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The skies look grimly⟦br⟧
And <qex>threaten</qex> present blusters.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To menace.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Threaten</er>,
<er>Menace</er>. <xex>Threaten</xex> is Anglo-Saxon, and
<xex>menace</xex> is Latin. As often happens, the former is the more
familiar term; the latter is more employed in formal style. We are
<xex>threatened</xex> with a drought; the country is <xex>menaced</xex>
with war.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By turns put on the suppliant and the lord:⟦br⟧
<qex>Threatened</qex> this moment, and the next implored.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Of the sharp ax⟦br⟧
Regardless, that o'er his devoted head⟦br⟧
Hangs <qex>menacing</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Somerville.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Threaten</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Threaten
<hw>Threat"en</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To use threats, or menaces;
also, to have a threatening appearance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though the seas <qex>threaten</qex>, they are merciful.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Threatener</ent>⟦br⟧
